value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;">Figure 9: Organisation Structure</h1><h1 style="margin-top: 0px;"><p style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 400;">It is no coincidence that organisation imitates product structure, where every department is like a component with its own interface and inner workings, each at a lower level of abstraction in the tree. They are not the same, but both structures inhabit the same abstract, recursive order of reality. A business system's efficacy and efficiency should be determined by its capacity to model and encapsulate this.</p></h1>" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry height="100" width="680" x="25" y="570" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </root> </mxGraphModel> </diagram> </mxfile>

h1.p: It is no coincidence that organisation imitates product structure, where every department is like a component with its own interface and inner workings, each at a lower level of abstraction in the tree. They are not the same, but both structures inhabit the same abstract, recursive order of reality. A business system's efficacy and efficiency should be determined by its capacity to model and encapsulate this.
